msgid "Introduction"
msgstr "Giới Thiệu -- Introduction"

msgid "The 2D video stabilization is a feature built on top of Blender's image feature tracking abilities: You can use some tracking points to remove shakiness, bumps and jerks from video footage. Typically, image stabilization is part of a 2D workflow to prepare and improve footage prior to further processing or modeling steps. This page helps to understand how it works, introduces related terms and concepts, describes the available interface controls in detail and finally gives some hints about usage in practice."
msgstr "The 2D video stabilization is a feature built on top of Blender's image feature tracking abilities: we use some *tracking points* to remove shakiness, bumps and jerks from video footage. Typically, image stabilization is part of a **2D workflow** to prepare and improve footage prior to further processing or modeling steps. This page helps to understand how it works, introduces related terms and concepts, describes the available interface controls in detail and finally gives some hints about usage in practice."

msgid "Typical usage scenarios of the stabilizer:"
msgstr "Typical **usage scenarios** of the stabilizer:"

msgid "Fix minor deficiencies (shaky tripod, jerk in camera movement)."
msgstr "Fix minor deficiencies (shaky Chân Máy Ảnh, jerk Vào Máy Quay Phim Chuyển Động)."

msgid "\"Poor man's steadycam\" (when a real steadycam was not available, affordable or applicable)."
msgstr "\"Poor man's steadycam\" (when a real steadycam was Đảo Nghịch Khả Dụng, affordable hoặc applicable)."

msgid "As a preparation for masking, matching and rotoscoping."
msgstr "As a preparation for -- Masking, matching và rotoscoping."

msgid "It is not uncommon for 2D stabilization to have to deal with somewhat imperfect and flawed footage."
msgstr "It is Đảo Nghịch uncommon for 2 Chiều -- 2D Ổn Định Hóa Tới have Tới deal với somewhat imperfect và flawed Cảnh Quay."

msgid "How It Works"
msgstr "Phương Pháp Điều Hành -- How It Works"

msgid "To detect spurious movement in a given shot, we'll assume a simplified model about this movement. We then try to fit the movement of tracked features with this simplified model to derive a compensation. Of course, this works only to the degree our model is adequate -- yet in practice, this simplified approach works surprisingly well even with rather complicated shots, where our basic assumption was just an approximation of much more elaborate movements."
msgstr "Tới detect spurious Chuyển Động Vào a given shot, we'll assume a simplified model Giới Thiệu cái/điều này Chuyển Động. We then try Tới Khít the Chuyển Động of tracked features với cái/điều này simplified model Tới derive a compensation. Of course, cái/điều này works only Tới the degree our model is adequate -- yet Vào practice, cái/điều này simplified approach works surprisingly well Đều Đặn với rather complicated shots, where our Đơn Giản assumption was just an approximation of much Nhiều/Lớn Hơn elaborate movements."

msgid "This simplified model underlying the 2D stabilization as implemented here assumes movement by an affine-linear transform:"
msgstr "This simplified model underlying the 2D stabilization as implemented here assumes movement by an **affine-linear transform**:"

msgid "The camera is pushed up/down/sideways by some translation component."
msgstr "The Máy Quay Phim is pushed Lên/Trên/Xuống/Dưới/sideways by some Dịch Chuyển/Phiên Dịch Thành Phần."

msgid "The image is then tilted and scaled around a pivot point (rotation center)."
msgstr "The Hình Ảnh is then tilted và scaled around a Điểm Tựa Điểm/Chấm (Xoay Chiều Trung Tâm)."

msgid "To compensate movement according to this simplified model, the 2D stabilizer proceeds in two steps. First we try to detect the translation offset from the weighted average of all *translation* tracking points. After compensating this translation component, we then use additional *rotation/scale* tracking points to detect rotation around a given pivot point. Again, we detect rotation and scale changes through a weighted average of all the rotation/scale tracking points given."
msgstr "Tới compensate Chuyển Động according Tới cái/điều này simplified model, the 2 Chiều -- 2D stabilizer proceeds Vào hai Số Bước. Đầu Tiên/Thứ Nhất we try Tới detect the Dịch Chuyển/Phiên Dịch Dịch Chuyển Từ the weighted Trung Bình Hóa of Toàn Bộ *Dịch Chuyển/Phiên Dịch* Giám Sát Số Điểm. Sau compensating cái/điều này Dịch Chuyển/Phiên Dịch Thành Phần, we then Sử Dụng Gia Lượng *Xoay Chiều/Tỷ Lệ* Giám Sát Số Điểm Tới detect Xoay Chiều around a given Điểm Tựa Điểm/Chấm. Again, we detect Xoay Chiều và Tỷ Lệ changes through a weighted Trung Bình Hóa of Toàn Bộ the Xoay Chiều/Tỷ Lệ Giám Sát Số Điểm given."

msgid "In the current version, the pivot point is anchored to the weight center of the translation tracking points. So effectively the detected translation is already factored out. In some cases this is not optimal, especially when tracks have gaps or do not cover the whole duration of the footage -- we plan further options to better control the pivot point in future releases."
msgstr "Vào the Hiện Tại Phiên Bản, the Điểm Tựa Điểm/Chấm is Cắm neo Tới the Trọng Lượng Trung Tâm of the Dịch Chuyển/Phiên Dịch Giám Sát Số Điểm. So effectively the detected Dịch Chuyển/Phiên Dịch is already factored Ra. Vào some cases cái/điều này is Đảo Nghịch optimal, especially when Giám Sát have gaps hoặc làm Đảo Nghịch cover the whole Độ Dài of the Cảnh Quay -- we plan further Tùy Chọn Tới better Điều Khiển the Điểm Tựa Điểm/Chấm Vào future releases."

msgid "Stabilization Tracks"
msgstr "Dấu Mốc Giám Sát Ổn Định -- Stabilization Tracks"

msgid "Thus, as foundation for any image stabilization, we need tracked image features to derive the movements. These tracking points or \"tracks\" can be established with Blender's :doc:`image feature tracking component </movie_clip/tracking/clip/introduction>` The right choice of points to track is somewhat tricky, yet crucial for successful image stabilization. Often, we're here because we'll have to deal with imperfect footage. In such cases, the averaging of tracks helps to work around image or tracking errors at some point. Moreover, when the footage contains perspective induced movements, symmetrically placed tracking points above and below the horizon can be used to cancel out spurious movement and get stabilization to the focal area in between."
msgstr "Thus, as foundation for any image stabilization, we need tracked image features to derive the movements. These *tracking points* or \"tracks\" can be established with Blender's :doc:`image feature tracking component </editors/movie_clip_editor/tracking/clip/introduction>` The right choice of points to track is somewhat tricky, yet crucial for successful image stabilization. Often, we're here because we'll have to deal with imperfect footage. In such cases, the *averaging of tracks* helps to work around image or tracking errors at some point. Moreover, when the footage contains *perspective induced movements*, symmetrically placed tracking points above and below the horizon can be used to cancel out spurious movement and get stabilization to the focal area in between."

msgid "Diverging movements caused by perspective."
msgstr "Diverging movements caused by Phối Cảnh Xa Gần."

msgid "Tracks can be added in two groups:"
msgstr "Giám Sát có thể be added Vào hai Nhóm:"

msgid "First of all is the list of tracks to be used to compensate for jumps in the camera location. From all the tracking points added to this group, we calculate a weighted average. We then try to keep this average location constant during the whole shot. Thus it is a good idea to use tracking markers close to and centered around the most important subject."
msgstr "Đầu Tiên/Thứ Nhất of Toàn Bộ is the Liệt Kê -- List of Giám Sát Tới be sử dụng Tới compensate for jumps Vào the Máy Quay Phim vị trí. Từ Toàn Bộ the Giám Sát Số Điểm added Tới cái/điều này Nhóm, we Tính Toán a weighted Trung Bình Hóa. We then try Tới -- Keep cái/điều này Trung Bình Hóa vị trí Hằng Số/Đồng Đều/Bất Biến during the whole shot. Thus it is a Tốt idea Tới Sử Dụng Giám Sát Các Dấu Mốc Đóng/Kín Tới và centered around the most important subject."

msgid "A second selection of tracks is used to keep the rotation and scale of the image constant. You may use the same tracks for both selections. But usually it is best to use tracking points with large distance from the image center, and symmetrically, on both sides, to capture the angular movements more precisely. Similar to the \"location\" case, we calculate an average angular contribution and then try to keep this value constant during the whole shot."
msgstr "A Thứ Hai Lựa Chọn of Giám Sát is sử dụng Tới -- Keep the Xoay Chiều và Tỷ Lệ of the Hình Ảnh Hằng Số/Đồng Đều/Bất Biến. You may Sử Dụng the same Giám Sát for Cả Hai selections. But usually it is best Tới Sử Dụng Giám Sát Số Điểm với Lớn Khoảng Cách Từ the Hình Ảnh Trung Tâm, và symmetrically, BẬT Cả Hai Số Cạnh, Tới capture the Góc movements Nhiều/Lớn Hơn precisely. Tương Đồng Tới the \"vị trí\" Kiểu Chữ, we Tính Toán an Trung Bình Hóa Góc contribution và then try Tới -- Keep cái/điều này Giá Trị Hằng Số/Đồng Đều/Bất Biến during the whole shot."

msgid "Footage, Image and Canvas"
msgstr "Đoạn Phim, Hình Ảnh, Mặt Toan -- Footage, Image and Canvas"

msgid "When talking about the movement stabilization of video, we have to distinguish several frames of reference. The image elements featured by the footage move around irregularly within the footage's original image boundaries -- this is the very reason why we are using the stabilizer. When our attempt at stabilization was successful, the image elements can be considered stable now, while in exchange the footage's image boundaries have taken on irregular movement and jump around in the opposite way. This is the immediate consequence of the stabilizer's activity."
msgstr "When talking Giới Thiệu the Chuyển Động Ổn Định Hóa of Phim Video, we have Tới distinguish several Khung Hình of Tham Chiếu. The Hình Ảnh Phần Tử featured by the Cảnh Quay Di Chuyển around irregularly within the Cảnh Quay's Gốc/Nguyên Bản Hình Ảnh Ranh Giới -- cái/điều này is the very reason why we are using the stabilizer. When our attempt Tại Ổn Định Hóa was successful, the Hình Ảnh Phần Tử có thể be considered stable Ngay Bây Giờ, while Vào exchange the Cảnh Quay's Hình Ảnh Ranh Giới have taken BẬT irregular Chuyển Động và Nhảy around Vào the opposite way. cái/điều này is the immediate consequence of the stabilizer's activity."

msgid "Since the actual image elements, i.e. the subject of our footage can be considered stable now, we may use these as a new frame of reference: we consider them attached to a fixed backdrop, which we call the canvas. Introducing this concept of a \"canvas\" helps to deal with deliberate movements of the camera. And beyond that, it yields an additional benefit: It is very frequent for the pixels of video footage to be non-square. So we have to stretch and expand those pixels, before we're able to perform any sensible rotation stabilization. Thus the canvas becomes, by definition, the reference for an undistorted display of the image contents."
msgstr "Since the actual image elements, i.e. the subject of our footage can be considered stable now, we may use these as a new frame of reference: we consider them attached to a fixed backdrop, which we call the **canvas**. Introducing this concept of a \"canvas\" helps to deal with deliberate movements of the camera. And beyond that, it yields an additional benefit: It is very frequent for the pixels of video footage to be *non-square*. So we have to stretch and expand those pixels, before we're able to perform any sensible rotation stabilization. Thus the canvas becomes, by definition, the reference for an undistorted display of the image contents."

msgid "But when the camera was moved intentionally, we have to consider yet another frame of reference beyond the canvas: namely the frame (or \"cadre\") of the final image we want to create. To understand this distinction, let's consider a hand-held, panning shot to the right: Since our camera was turned towards the right side, the actual image contents move towards the left side *within* the original image frame. But let's assume the stabilizer was successful with \"fixing\" any image contents relative to the canvas -- which in turn means, that the original image boundaries start to move irregularly towards the right side, and the contents of the image will begin to disappear gradually behind the left boundary of the original image. After some amount of panning, we'll have lost all of our original contents and just see an empty black image backdrop. The only solution to deal with that problem is to move the final image frame along to the right, thus following the originally intended panning movement. Of course, this time, we do want to perform this newly added panning movement in a smooth and clean way."
msgstr "But when the Máy Quay Phim was moved intentionally, we have Tới consider yet another Khung Hình of Tham Chiếu beyond the Toan: namely the Khung Hình (hoặc \"cadre\") of the Kết Thúc/Kết Cục/Cuối Cùng Hình Ảnh we want Tới Tạo. Tới understand cái/điều này distinction, let's consider a hand-held, Lia -- Panning shot Tới the phải: Since our Máy Quay Phim was turned towards the phải Bên/Mặt, the actual Hình Ảnh contents Di Chuyển towards the trái Bên/Mặt *within* the Gốc/Nguyên Bản Hình Ảnh Khung Hình. But let's assume the stabilizer was successful với \"fixing\" Bất Cứ Hình Ảnh contents Tương Đối Tới the Toan -- cái mà/tức Vào turn means, that the Gốc/Nguyên Bản Hình Ảnh Ranh Giới Khởi Đầu Tới Di Chuyển irregularly towards the phải Bên/Mặt, và the contents of the Hình Ảnh will begin Tới disappear gradually behind the trái Ranh Giới of the Gốc/Nguyên Bản Hình Ảnh. Sau some Số/Lượng of Lia -- Panning, we'll have lost Toàn Bộ of our Gốc/Nguyên Bản contents và just see an Phần Tử Trống/Rỗng Màu Đen Hình Ảnh Phông Nền. The only solution Tới deal với that problem is Tới Di Chuyển the Kết Thúc/Kết Cục/Cuối Cùng Hình Ảnh Khung Hình along Tới the phải, thus following the originally intended Lia -- Panning Chuyển Động. Of course, cái/điều này Thời Gian, we làm want Tới perform cái/điều này newly added Lia -- Panning Chuyển Động Vào a Làm Mịn/Trơn Tru và Dọn Dẹp way."

msgid "Stabilizing a panning shot."
msgstr "Stabilizing a Lia -- Panning shot."

msgid "Restoring the expected camera movement."
msgstr "Restoring the expected Máy Quay Phim Chuyển Động."

msgid "To allow for such a compensation and to reintroduce deliberate panning, or tilting and zoom of the resulting image, the stabilizer offers a dedicated set of controls: *Expected position*, *Expected rotation* and *Expected scale*. These act like the controls of a virtual camera filming the contents we have fixed onto the canvas. By animating those parameters, we're able to perform all kinds of deliberate camera movements in a smooth fashion."
msgstr "To allow for such a compensation and to reintroduce deliberate panning, or tilting and zoom of the resulting image, the stabilizer offers a dedicated set of controls: *Expected position*, *Expected rotation* and *Expected scale*. These act like the controls of a virtual camera filming the contents we have fixed onto the canvas. By *animating* those parameters, we're able to perform all kinds of deliberate camera movements in a smooth fashion."

msgid "The \"Dancing\" Black Borders"
msgstr "-- The \"Dancing\" Black Borders"

msgid "As explained above, when we succeed with stabilizing the image contents, the boundaries of the original footage start to jump around in the opposite direction of the movements compensated. This is inevitable -- yet very annoying, since due to the irregular nature of these movements, these \"dancing black borders\" tend to distract attention from the actual subject and introduce an annoying restlessness. Thus our goal must be to hide those dancing borders as good as possible. A simple solution is to add a small amount of zoom. Sometimes we'll also need to animate the parameter *Expected* position in order to keep the image centered as good as we can -- this helps to reduce the amount of zoom necessary to remove those annoying borders."
msgstr "As explained above, when we succeed với stabilizing the Hình Ảnh contents, the Ranh Giới of the Gốc/Nguyên Bản Cảnh Quay Khởi Đầu Tới Nhảy around Vào the opposite Chiều Hướng of the movements compensated. cái/điều này is inevitable -- yet very annoying, since due Tới the irregular nature of these movements, these \"dancing Màu Đen Khoanh Ranh Giới\" tend Tới distract attention Từ the actual subject và introduce an annoying restlessness. Thus our Đích must be Tới Ẩn those dancing Khoanh Ranh Giới as Tốt as possible. A Đơn Giản solution is Tới Cộng Thêm a Nhỏ Số/Lượng of Thu-Phóng. Sometimes we'll also need Tới Hoạt Họa the parameter *Expected* Vị Trí Vào Theo Thứ Tự Tới -- Keep the Hình Ảnh centered as Tốt as we có thể -- cái/điều này helps Tới reduce the Số/Lượng of Thu-Phóng necessary Tới Xóa those annoying Khoanh Ranh Giới."

msgid "The *Autoscale* function can be used to find the minimal amount of zoom just sufficient to remove those black borders completely. However, if the camera jumps a lot, the autoscale function often zooms in too much, especially since this calculation aims at finding a single, static zoom factor for the whole duration of the footage. When this happens, you'll typically get overall better results with animating both the zoom factor and the expected position manually."
msgstr "The *Tự Động Đổi Tỷ Lệ* function có thể be sử dụng Tới Lùng Tìm the Tối Thiểu Số/Lượng of Thu-Phóng just sufficient Tới Xóa those Màu Đen Khoanh Ranh Giới completely. However, if the Máy Quay Phim jumps a lot, the Tự Động Đổi Tỷ Lệ function often zooms Vào too much, especially since cái/điều này calculation aims Tại finding a Đơn/Một Cánh, Tĩnh Tại Thu-Phóng Hệ Số for the whole Độ Dài of the Cảnh Quay. When cái/điều này happens, you'll typically get overall better results với -- Animating Cả Hai the Thu-Phóng Hệ Số và the expected Vị Trí thủ công."

